TopicTitle: [PART, 1.0.2] Anatid Robotics / MuMech - MechJeb - Autopilot - Historical thread

Articles.Content: As I said I doubt it's MJ related. The class listed in the log are stock only so I guess you stumbled on one of the stock bugs

Congratulations!

The bounding box debug button (MechJeb #256) has found the source of the docking AP problem.

As has already been reported by CFIRickM http://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/threads/12384-PART-0-23-5-Anatid-Robotics-MuMech-MechJeb-Autopilot-v2-2-1?p=1169988&viewfull=1#post1169988

It was Real Chutes for me too. Confirmed the fix is to upgrade to Real Chutes v1.1

On approach to my "KSS" station MechJeb was seeing the parachute on the station's escape pod ("Soyuz" if you will) as already being deployed. Does this scenario sound familiar to anyone else?

I can't tell you how happy I am that this has been solved and fixed.

Thank you so much.

I use KSP for Linux 64 bit but it would appear that is not relevant. Here follows my experience with the debug information for completeness. Sorry it makes for a long post.

Change your perspective a little. Don't think so much in terms of mass, think in terms of delta-V. If you look carefully at each successful design and watch the dV numbers, you'll notice that (virtually) every rocket uses the same dV no matter the size or mass. Build your rockets around the dV numbers instead of mass. Important: delta-V is not the same as volume of fuel. It's how much velocity you can get out of that combination of engine and fuel volume (and mass). Using FAR, LKO takes about 4000 dV (vac), plus-or-minus, to get to 200 km, regardless of the number of stages. This value is probably different if you're not using FAR.

I usually build my booster stages, whether single-core or center-core-with-strapons, around a total (vac) dV of 2800. Rockets typically climb above 50 km with this value. My sustainer is generally about 2700 dV (vac), of which half (or less) gets used to complete the climb-to-apoapsis and circularization. My circularizations range from 90-130 dV (vac). These dV numbers are relatively constant for every design, using the stock planet sizes and FAR.

As for the launch path, try to start the turn as low as possible. The quicker you can start the turn, the quicker the rocket begins to accelerate with gravity assist. I have my curve beginning at 1 km. You may need to "tweak" your engines for optimal gimbal range, as some engines don't always have enough swing to handle the needed corrective action. YMMV.

Trial-and-error was how I figured out the best curve numbers. I'm using a value of 75 at the moment, with a horizontal altitude of 65 km. The horizontal altitude only means the rocket should have "leveled out" to pro-grade by the time it reaches this altitude. I'm often pointing below the horizon before I reach this altitude, so I might need to tweak it a little myself.

Hope this helps.

Now, to new business: I have a suggestion for a slight adjustment of the functioning of the Rendezvous Autopilot. I have no idea if this would be practical to implement, or even if it's possible at all, but here we go...

Currently, when I engage the 'RendAuto', as the toolbar button says, my MJ enabled craft plots the intercept just fine, matches planes, sets up phasing orbits, all hunky dory. When it gets close, or, well, anytime it's 'plotting course for intercept', I notice that MJ attempts to aim the ship directly at the target craft, and then plot a burn to try to stop short of the target by the distance set in the Autopilot, let's say 100m for this example. Depending in conditions, this can lead to a plotted 'closest approach distance' measured in, at times, millimeters. So if MJ is just a bit late on the node for the braking burn, I end up with a nice Kessler debris cloud and short 2 ships, not to mention a few Kerbals too.

So here's my proposal: when I set the 'desired final distance' of 100m, I'd like to see MJ plot a course that will take my ship PAST the target with a 'closest approach distance' of NO LESS THAN 100 meters. Basically, plot a course to a tangent point on a circle with a 100m radius, centered on the target, instead of plotting a course DIRECTLY AT the target and then trying to stop before breaking the surface of a 100m radius sphere centered on the target, get it? This way, if the burn is a little late (or I ran out of fuel or power, or I forgot to stage the engines, whatever) the ship safely bypasses the target with no risk of collision, or of giving me a heart attack with a 'bullet burn' level near-hit, as I've also experienced several times!

Again, the above may not be easily done or even possible, but I thought I'd throw the idea out here as food for thought.
